Bucky Brooks 2025 NFL mock draft 4.0: Steelers land Shedeur Sanders; Cowboys, Broncos select RBs

Published: Apr 22, 2025 at 02:12 PM
Bucky Brooks

NFL.com Analyst

  • Final mocks: Jeremiah
  • Zierlein
  • Parr
  • Davis
  • Brooks
  • Edholm
  • Reuter
  • Ross
  • Filice

It's finally the week of the 2025 NFL Draft -- and before the event gets underway in Green Bay, Wisconsin, I'm here to take my fourth and final attempt at projecting how the first round will play out on Thursday night.

Any trades that are struck will certainly reshape the Round 1 pecking order, but in this simulation, I'm keeping everything as it stands right now in hopes of providing the most realistic forecast for as many teams as possible.

Let's get to the picks!

Pick
1
Tennessee Titans
Cam Ward
Miami QB Senior

As the Titans new franchise QB1, Ward would add the kind of talent, toughness and tenacity the franchise has lacked since Steve Air McNair was under center in Tennessee.

Pick
2
Cleveland Browns
Travis Hunter
Colorado WR/CB Junior

The two-way standout is a superstar in the making as a big-play pass catcher and shutdown corner. Hunters unique skills would give Kevin Stefanski a Shohei Ohtani-esque weapon to utilize on offense and defense. 

Pick
3
New York Giants
Abdul Carter
Penn State Edge Junior

Bypassing a chance to land a potential franchise quarterback is risky, but the Giants could take a disruptive playmaker to enhance a pass rush that features three quarterback hunters (Brian Burns, Dexter Lawrence and Kayvon Thibodeaux) on the front line.

Pick
4
New England Patriots
Will Campbell
LSU OT Junior

Protecting Drake Maye is a top priority for a front office that wants to see the franchise quarterback flourish in Year 2. 

Pick
5
Jacksonville Jaguars
Mason Graham
Michigan DT Junior

The safest pick in the draft would give the Jaguars a blue-chip defender in the middle of a defensive line that needs more hard hat and lunch pail guys. 

Pick
6
Las Vegas Raiders
Ashton Jeanty
Boise State RB Junior

Pete Carrolls apparent desire to feature a dominant rushing attack makes the Boise State standout the sensible pick to serve as his lead back. 

Pick
7
New York Jets
Tyler Warren
Penn State TE Senior

Adding a big-bodied pass-catcher between the hashes would help Justin Fields settle in as a passer in an offense rooted in play-action concepts. Warren is a versatile playmaker with the route-running ability and ball skills to move the chains consistently with a ball-control approach. 

Pick
8
Carolina Panthers
Jalon Walker
Georgia LB Junior

Upgrading the defensive front with a hybrid linebacker who boasts pass-rushing skills could help the Panthers create more chaos at the point of attack. 

Pick
9
New Orleans Saints
Will Johnson
Michigan CB Junior

The talented technician would give the Saints a blue-chip CB1 to feature in a zone-based system that places a premium on vision-and-break playmakers. 

Pick
10
Chicago Bears
Kelvin Banks Jr.
Texas OT Junior

New head coach Ben Johnsons experience with a dominant line while running the offense for division-rival Detroit could prompt him to add more resources to the Bears front, even after it was fortified in free agency. Banks is a natural left tackle with the athleticism and shadowboxing skills to protect Caleb Williams blind side.

Pick
11
San Francisco 49ers
Walter Nolen
Mississippi DT Junior

Adding more talent and athleticism to the defensive front will enable Nick Bosa and Co. to get back to their disruptive ways at the line of scrimmage under DC Robert Saleh.

Pick
12
Dallas Cowboys
Omarion Hampton
North Carolina RB Junior

The team needs a true RB1 to steady an offense that is always better when it operates with a run-first premise. 

Pick
13
Miami Dolphins
Jahdae Barron
Texas CB Senior

Jalen Ramseys potential imminent departure could lead Barron to fill two spots as a CB/nickel defender. 

Pick
14
Indianapolis Colts
Armand Membou
Missouri OT Junior

With 29-year-old Braden Smith entering Year 8 of his career, the Colts could acquire their right tackle of the future here. As a big-bodied edge blocker with twinkle toes and heavy hands, Membou has the star power general manager Chris Ballard tends to covet in a top prospect.

Pick
15
Atlanta Falcons
Mike Green
Marshall Edge Junior (RS)

The teams desperation for an elite pass rusher could make Green the pick here. The Marshall standout possesses the first-step quickness and explosiveness to harass quarterbacks off the edge. 

Pick
16
Arizona Cardinals
Derrick Harmon
Oregon DT Junior (RS)

The hard-nosed interior force would be a nice fit in Arizona's D-line as a disruptive defender with heavy hands and a high-revving motor.

Pick
17
Cincinnati Bengals
Shemar Stewart
Texas A&M Edge Junior

Stewart still needs some development, but he's athletic and could generate strong sack numbers, especially if Trey Hendrickson sticks around, setting the rookie up to feed off the veteran's presence.

Pick
18
Seattle Seahawks
Tetairoa McMillan
Arizona WR Junior

After trading away DK Metcalf and releasing Tyler Lockett this offseason, the Seahawks could add a big-bodied pass-catcher to occupy the role of red-zone weapon.

Pick
19
Tampa Bay Buccaneers
Jihaad Campbell
Alabama LB Junior

Lavonte David is back for Year 14 -- but Todd Bowles could pick the 35-year-old linebacker's successor here. Presuming his recovery from a torn labrum goes smoothly, Campbells versatility would give the Buccaneers a second-level defender with playmaking and pass-rush potential.

Pick
20
Denver Broncos
TreVeyon Henderson
Ohio State RB Senior

Sean Payton wants a feature back with big-play potential in the rotation. Hendersons speed and explosiveness could give the Super Bowl-winning coach Alvin Kamara vibes when he's contemplating how to utilize the Ohio State standout. 

Pick
21
Pittsburgh Steelers
Shedeur Sanders
Colorado QB Senior

Mike Tomlin could view Sanders as the perfect quarterback for his squad. With his confidence, moxie and pinpoint passing skills, the Colorado star might ignite a dormant offense that has already added some star power this offseason. 

Pick
22
Los Angeles Chargers
Colston Loveland
Michigan TE Junior

Surrounding Justin Herbert with more playmakers should be a top priority for the Chargers. As a flex tight end with sticky hands and wide receiver-like route-running skills, Loveland could create mismatches in the passing game. 

Pick
23
Green Bay Packers
Maxwell Hairston
Kentucky CB Junior (RS)

The playmaking cover corner is the ideal ballhawk to play in Jeff Hafleys system. Hairston excels as a see ball, get ball defender with superb instincts, awareness and diagnostic skills.

Pick
24
Minnesota Vikings
Nick Emmanwori
South Carolina S Junior

Emmanwori can learn from Harrison Smith, who has been in the Vikings' backfield for 13 seasons, before sliding in as the next potential fixture at safety in Minnesota.

Pick
25
Houston Texans
Tyler Booker
Alabama IOL Junior

The 300-plus-pound bully is a tone-setter at the point of attack. Booker mauls defenders as a heavy-handed blocker with a violent approach. 

Pick
26
Los Angeles Rams
Josh Simmons
Ohio State OT Junior (RS)

The talented edge blocker might be too talented to bypass at this selection. Simmons athleticism and movement skills could make him a star early in his career. 

Pick
27
Baltimore Ravens
Mykel Williams
Georgia Edge Junior

GM Eric DeCosta and head coach John Harbaugh have a knack for finding quality players at the end of the first round. With his athleticism and pass-rushing potential, Williams could flourish in the Ravens aggressive defense. 

Pick
28
Detroit Lions
Donovan Jackson
Ohio State OG Senior

In terms of temperament and physicality, Jackson is perfectly suited to help the Lions continue to dominate up front from the jump.

Pick
29
Washington Commanders
Matthew Golden
Texas WR Junior

What do the Commanders do to help Jayden Daniels take another step forward? Use a first-round pick on Golden, who led Texas in both receiving yards (987) and scoring grabs (nine) last season.

Pick
30
Buffalo Bills
Kenneth Grant
Michigan DT Junior

Buffalo's depth chart features plenty of pass-rushing talent; the 6-foot-4, 331-pound Grant's presence up front could help shore up a run defense that ranked 19th in the NFL in yards allowed per rush attempt in 2024. 

Pick
31
Kansas City Chiefs
Trey Amos
Mississippi CB Senior

Adding an outside corner would enable the Chiefs to move Trent McDuffie back to his natural nickel spot. Amos length, instincts and bump-and-run skills mesh well with the teams defensive scheme.

Pick
32
Philadelphia Eagles
Donovan Ezeiruaku
Boston College Edge Senior

The relentless, energetic Ezeiruaku knows how to harass the passer, based on his 16.5 sacks (second-most in the FBS) last season. He's an ideal match for the Eagles.
